diff:1620967299:1620532198:=73,85d72%0a%3c #foxbegin 210514-044139-145250#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Navajo verbs %0a%3c -> - meng_s%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c The most prominent part of Navajo grammar is perhaps the Navajo verb. A Navajo verb encapsulates a wealth of information through prefixation. In fact, a single Navajo verb can be equivalent to a complete sentence in English. There are up to 10 prefixes that can be added to verb stems, though some prefixes are mutually dependent or exclusive. In a video (linked below), the phrase “I kissed Sally”, “Sally nánétz'ó̜ó̜z” in Navajo, is explained. While the verb “kissed” in English is only composed of the verb stem /kiss/ and the past tense morpheme /-ed/, “nánétz'ó̜ó̜z” encodes information on number, subject, tense as well as location. What is even more interesting is that transitive verbs describing the same action can have different verb stems depending on the physical characteristics of the object. For example, the verb “consume” is /-yí̜í̜h/ when the object of consumption is unspecified, /-ˀaaɬ/ for consuming hard, compact objects like sweets and /-tsˀééh/ when consuming mushy matter.%0a%3c %0a%3c Video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OeWv1wmdzTY%0a%3c Verb stems of consumption: https://www.researchgate.net/figure/15-Navajo-verb-stems-of-consumption-taken-from-Young-Morgan-1987-251-263-875_tbl2_278028506%0a%3c Navajo grammar: https://repository.arizona.edu/bitstream/handle/10150/126385/azu_alc_cp_n16_9_34_w.pdf?sequence=1%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210514-044139-145250#%0a
